<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Chapter III: A New Life</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The morning sunlight beamed through the window of an unfamiliar house. It stretched across the room towards a futon where a young man was lying down in. As the sunlight shined across his face, the young man slowly woke up and tossed himself around in bed a bit before opening his eyes. Pulling the sheets off of his face, the young man revealed himself to be none other than Hiru. He sat up straight and held his head, sort of rubbing his forehead as well, trying to wake himself up. It was then he realized that he was not waking up in an alley or street corner as he had expected to, and became extremely curious as to where he was, since the last thing he remembered was his confrontation with Jinshira. He didn’t want to get out of bed, however, since it had been almost four or five years since he had slept in one. Hiru managed to step away from the bed and walked towards the window. He slid the window open and peered outside, finding himself in a place that felt somewhat familiar to him. For a few moments then on, he tried to pull out of his head why this place seemed so familiar, but to no avail. He gave up and walked across the room towards the door, sliding it open and looking down the hallway. “Hello?” He shouted down the corridor. It was just then that someone walked out into the hallway—an elderly woman who was carrying a basket of laundry. “Oh!” She exclaimed as she noticed Hiru. Running up to him, she put down her load of laundry and placed her hand on Hiru’s forehead. “Are you feeling okay?” She asked. Hiru backed off for a moment and placed his own hand on his forehead for some reason. The elderly woman lightly bowed at Hiru and apologized to him. “I’m sorry, this must be very awkward for you.” She rose from her light bow and greeted him. “Let my introduce myself. My name is Ichijo.” Hiru was still feeling out of place and looked to the side as he replied to the old lady. “I’m Hagara Hiru.” Ichijo knelt down and picked up the basket of laundry that she put down a moment ago. “Well, it’s certainly nice to finally known your name. You’ve been asleep for two days straight, now.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Where am I?” Hiru asked, still wondering about why this placed seemed so familiar to him, and now a bit more curious as to how he ended up wherever he was. Ichijo staggered a bit, having trouble holding up her heavy basket of laundry. Hiru quickly rushed to her aid and helped so that she would not drop it or hurt herself. “Oh, thank you. What a nice boy you are.” Hiru turned his nose up at Ichijo, a little steamed about being called a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>boy</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. “I’m not a little boy! I’m fifteen years old!” Ichijo took up the basket of laundry and apologized to Hiru once again. “I’m sorry,” she said, smiling. “Why don’t you join my husband and I for breakfast? You must be incredibly hungry.” Ichijo smiled again and turned around, walking down the hall as Hiru watched her from the door. Before turning the corner, she paused for a moment and turned her head around towards Hiru. “Oh, that’s true. I almost forgot you asked about where you were,” she began, “You’re at our house in Kyoto, so please make yourself home.” Ichijo smiled at Hiru once more and then turned back around, continuing down the hall until turning the corner and walking out of sight. “In Kyoto,&quot; Hiru muttered to himself. &quot;I’m In Kyoto?” He had a hard time sinking this information in, as the name of the city obviously meant something special to him; be it good or not.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The table was just prepared for breakfast—decorated with rice balls and miso soup. Ichijo sat herself down after just setting the table, and her husband Kenja, having already said his grace, was well into eating his food by now. Ichijo poured her husband’s drink, and then her own. She needn’t give thanks for the meal since it was she who prepared it. After gulping down half of his glass of tea and setting it down, Kenja let loose an immense sigh. “Say, Ichijo, didn’t you tell me that young boy woke up? Where is he? Isn’t he going to come eat?” Ichijo turned her head to look over at Hiru’s spot on the table that she prepared for him, wondering if he was going to get out of his room and come to breakfast. “I don’t know.” Kenja reached over with his chopsticks to Hiru’s plate, but Ichijo batted his hand away with her own pair. “He must be getting hungry, though.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp From around the corner of the hallway and into the breakfast room came Hiru. He was a little surprised when he saw all of the food that was on his plate, and hurried over to his seat and gave thanks. “Itadakimasu!” He shouted out before shoving food into his mouth. Ichijo then leaned over the table and poured Hiru’s drink. “I knew you had to have been hungry—just look at you.” Hiru took up the tall glass of tea and washed down his food, calming down for a moment after realizing that he was making an animal out of himself. “I’m sorry. It’s just that I haven’t had a good meal in a long time.” Ichijo smiled and nodded her head. “Don’t even dare apologize. Go ahead and fill yourself up.”<br>
